2.4.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.6:

2.4.1: a) A flexible approach would be better as it would fit the model better and reduce bias. A large sample size would benefit with a flexible model as opposed to an inflexible one.

  1. A flexible approach would be worse as it would overfit the data as the sample size is small.

  2. Flexible would be better as there would be a greater degree of freedom and a flexible model would obtain a better fit.

  3. A flexible model would be worse as flexibility would just increase the amount of variance.

2.4.3:

2.4.6:

A parametric approach makes an assumption for the functional form or shape of f. It reduces the problem of estimating f down to one of estimating the parameters. Non parametric models do not make an assumption for the functional form or shape of f. It requires a very large number of observations to accurately estimate f.

The advantages of parametric to regression or classification is that not many observations are needed as compared to a non parametric approach and it simplifies it to just estimating the parameters for a model for f.

The disadvantages are that the model chosen for f could be wrong which would inaccurately estimate f or overfit the observations if more flexible models are used.

2.4.7:

  1. Obs. 1 distance = 3 Obs. 2 distance = 2 Obs. 3 distance = sqrt(10) ~ 3.16 Obs. 4 distance = sqrt(5) ~ 2.236 Obs. 5 distance = sqrt(2) ~ 1.4 Obs. 6 distance = sqrt(3) ~ 1.7

  2. The observation will be green. This is because when K=1, the closest observation is Obs. 5

  3. The observation will be Red. When K =3, observations 1, 3 and 5 are closest. 1 and 3 are red while 5 is green. Thus, our prediction would be red.

  4. We would expect K to be small. This is because a small K would be more flexible and fit a non-linear boundary while a large K would try to fit a more linear boundary as it would take many points into consideration.
